We will use the polling data from 3rd wave for North Carolinas 9th Congressional District. We have distributed a copy of this data with the problem set. Make sure to use the copy we have distributed. Do not download it directly from the web. Make sure to read the section of the syllabus devoted to problem sets and how to do them. NC 9 has been in the news lately . . .

Question 1

There were X respondents who supported the Democratic candidate.

There were X more respondents who favored the Republican candidate than who were Undecided.

There are two gender variables (gender and gender_combined). There are X individuals for whom these variables have different values.

There are X respondents listed as White under race_eth who are not listed as White under file_race_black.

The first response of Rep came X minutes (rounded to the nearest minute) before the first response of Dem.

Question 2: Create (approximately) this chart

You must get the same shape (5 x 3), ordering of rows/columns and the same numerical results. But, as you saw with my example from class this week, it can be difficult to get everything to match. Morever, there are some flaws (like a lack of title and source, for example) with this plot that you should fix. The key point is that your code comments should explain, what you did and why you did it that way. If you think DEM. is a stupid column name, then use a better one, while explaining your reasoning in the code comments. Hint: The code we worked through in class is not a bad starting point, but it will not work out of the box. The data from NC 9 is more problematic, so you will need yo make some changes to the code. Our best advice is to examine the results at each step as you go through constructing your analysis pipeline.

Question 4

Look at the first few chapters of Data Visualization: A practical introduction by Kieran Healy. It is excellent. Chapter 5 provides several examples of how to plot categorical data. Make an interesting plot using this data, selecting the variables to use from this list: response, ager, educ, file_race, gender, party_id, phone_type, genballot, and timestamp. Obviously, you cant create a plot which uses all of these variables. Indeed, most of you will just use two of them. But try to find something interesting and present it in a way of which Healy would approve. Your plot should be different from any other students. Make lots of comments in your code about why you made the choices you did.
